  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions\n- Helps detect and prevent money laundering\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Established criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n\n3. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Enhanced anti-money laundering provisions\n- Increased reporting requirements and enforcement capabilities\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Updated and modernized existing anti-money laundering regulations\n- Expanded reporting requirements and enforcement mechanisms\n\nAt the federal level, money laundering is primarily prosecuted under:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\nAdditionally, many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws.\n\nThese statutes collectively provide a comprehensive legal framework for detecting, preventing, and prosecuting money laundering activities.",
